{"key":"post-10579821","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10579821</id>\n<content>They don't eat much and rarely lay eggs in the substrate, and if it's fully colonized, the larvae can't do much anyway and usually die.&amp;nbsp; They're mostly just looking for a meal.&amp;nbsp; Don't spray poison on them.&amp;nbsp; Sticky traps are probably the best control if there's a lot.&amp;nbsp; For only three or four, just ignore them.&amp;nbsp; Some gnats go for wine or beer, but others don't.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Two common places they come from are houseplants that have been outdoors and brought back in, and the bathtub drain.&amp;nbsp; Check both.&amp;nbsp; If they're in the bathtub drain, a bit of drano will nuke them.&amp;nbsp; Pour it in and then put a rag over the drain to hold the fumes and prevent them from escaping.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10579930</next>\n<prev>10579798</prev>\n<first>10578605</first>\n<last>10580648</last>\n<when>1246082081</when>\n<utime>06/27/09 08:54 AM</utime>\n</post>"}